Transformation Rules:

Vertical Stacking: Convert the left-to-right flow into a top-to-bottom hierarchy.

Focal Point: Identify the primary central graphic (the 'hero' element) and place it in the optical center of the square.

Header/Footer: Move top-level branding or status indicators to the top 15% of the frame. Move technical telemetry and 'system' metrics to the bottom 15%.

Component Grouping: Stack secondary data cards (forecasts, decisions, or sidebars) vertically between the hero element and the footer.

Visual Integrity: Maintain the exact color palette, typography, and 'cyber' aesthetic of the original. Adjust any connecting lines or glow effects to flow vertically to accommodate the narrower width.

payload.text: Use these rules when generating React/TypeScript animation components for a Next.js app: Required directives and imports Add 'use client'; at the very top of the file (before any imports). Use next/navigation for routing: import { useRouter } from 'next/navigation', then router.push('/path'). Do not use react-router-dom or useNavigate. Dependencies and APIs Do not import or use @google/genai or GoogleGenAI. For AI-like behavior, use static text or randomized entries from a hardcoded array. Use only icons available in lucide-react (e.g. CheckCircle2 instead of CloudCheck). Prefer common icons from the library. React/JSX rules If using React.memo(), use a named function so it gets a display name: React.memo(function ComponentName(props) { ... }) In JSX children, wrap comments in braces: {/* comment */} or {'// code-style comment'}. Escape quotes in JSX text: use " or {' " '} instead of raw ". TypeScript Avoid any. Add explicit types for event handlers, refs, and state. Refs: useRef(null) (or the correct element type), never useRef(null) alone. Event handlers: type as (e: MouseEvent) or (e: React.MouseEvent) as needed.
